<Author>bigmutt
<Content>Two-star at best; you can do much better than this one. We stayed a week so this is not based on just a few days.over-priced, far from everything, breakfast included but you better get there at 7 a.m. if you want some luke-warm eggs and sausages: they're gone by 8 and they don't replace most of the items that run out early, like croissants, a few pieces of fruit, etc. but there's cold-cuts and juice and cereal  yogurt  breads; great home-made wholegrain bread. Oh, and the coolest automatic coffee machine ever!! Has snotty morning/daytime receptionist but nice one late-afternoon and evenings; small noisy rooms, NO A/C !! bad mattresses, tiny shower but effective; no electric outlet in bathroom for hairdryer or shaver or whatever; no reading lights, tiny t.v. set, windows open just a crack so you'd better hope for cool weather if you're here in summer. But: free wireless LAN, free bathrobe, and LOTS of red, satiny drapes, pillows, bedcovers etc to simulate an Italian decorated hotel. Beautiful from the outside, well-worn on the inside.The general area is pleasant enough, but in the evening, no inexpensive restaurants nearby: only a snack grill (Doener sandwiches from Turkey, and hamburgers). There's a nice little supermarket 3 blocks away, though. And during the day (if you're hanging around your hotel instead of being out in the city doing tourist stuff) there are some small restaurants and bakeries, etc. in the area, and especially down in the U-Bahn below street-level.U-Bahn : to get to ANY of the attractions you'll need to transfer at least once, usually twice.If a small red canopy over your bed and heavy red curtains, etc. is REALLY important to you, you may like this place, but I'd say pass on this one; there's much better hotels in the 100-dollar per night range.Like I said, we spent a week, and it was no-where near as good a value as our week in Munich was. Far from it. 
